<!--
  STACK question: solving a 2x2 system with the matrix inverse (word problem).
  CBC Grade 11, Matrices I. Converted from a "tech club sells Basic/Pro kits"
  exercise and fully randomised.

  DESIGN-BACKWARDS RANDOMISATION.
  We choose the two prices first (nice multiples of Ksh 100, distinct), then pick
  the daily quantities from a curated list of 2x2 integer matrices that all have a
  positive, non-zero determinant and non-proportional rows. We then COMPUTE the
  daily takings from quantities x prices. This guarantees:
    * the system is always consistent,
    * the unique solution is exactly the chosen integer prices, and
    * the determinant is a sensible positive integer (so the "inverse exists"
      reasoning is clean every time).
  Dimensions of variation: the coefficient matrix (11 curated cases) and the two
  prices. No degenerate variants (no zero entries, det != 0, prices distinct).
-->
<quiz>
  <question type="stack">
    <name>
      <text>Matrices I - solve a 2x2 system using the inverse (kits word problem)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>A tech club sells two types of kits: <b>Basic</b> and <b>Pro</b>.</p>
<ul>
<li>On the first day they sell \({@n11@}\) Basic and \({@n12@}\) Pro kits and collect <b>Ksh {@R1@}</b>.</li>
<li>On another day they sell \({@n21@}\) Basic and \({@n22@}\) Pro kits and collect <b>Ksh {@R2@}</b>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Let \(b\) be the price (in Ksh) of a Basic kit and \(p\) the price of a Pro kit.</p>

<p><b>(a)</b> Complete the matrix equation that models this situation (fill in the coefficient matrix and the right-hand side):</p>
<p style="margin-left:1em;">[[input:ans1]] \(\left[\begin{array}{c} b \\ p \end{array}\right] \;=\;\) [[input:ans2]]</p>
<p>[[validation:ans1]] [[validation:ans2]]</p>

<p><b>(b)</b> The inverse of the coefficient matrix exists provided its determinant is non-zero. Compute the determinant of the coefficient matrix:</p>
<p style="margin-left:1em;">determinant \(=\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>

<p><b>(c)</b> Using the inverse of the \(2\times 2\) matrix, find the price of each kit.</p>
<p style="margin-left:1em;">Basic kit: Ksh [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]]</p>
<p style="margin-left:1em;">Pro kit: Ksh [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p><b>(a)</b> Each row is one day. The number of Basic and Pro kits sold multiply the unknown prices \(b\) and \(p\) to give that day's takings:</p>
\[ {@ta_M@}\left[\begin{array}{c} b \\ p \end{array}\right] = {@ta_rev@}. \]

<p><b>(b)</b> For a \(2\times2\) matrix \(\left[\begin{array}{cc}a&b\\c&d\end{array}\right]\) the determinant is \(ad-bc\):</p>
\[ \det M = ({@n11@})({@n22@}) - ({@n12@})({@n21@}) = {@det_ta@}. \]
<p>Since the determinant is non-zero, \(M^{-1}\) exists and the system has a unique solution.</p>

<p><b>(c)</b> For \(M=\left[\begin{array}{cc}a&b\\c&d\end{array}\right]\), \(M^{-1}=\dfrac{1}{ad-bc}\left[\begin{array}{cc}d&-b\\-c&a\end{array}\right]\). Here</p>
\[ M^{-1} = \frac{1}{ {@det_ta@} }\,{@adj_M@}. \]
<p>Multiplying the inverse by the takings vector gives the prices:</p>
\[ \left[\begin{array}{c} b \\ p \end{array}\right] = M^{-1}{@ta_rev@} = \frac{1}{ {@det_ta@} }{@ev(adj_M . ta_rev, simp)@} = {@price@}. \]
<p>So a Basic kit costs <b>Ksh {@pb@}</b> and a Pro kit costs <b>Ksh {@pp@}</b>.</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
